Package: RaschR
Type: Package
Title: Pairwise Conditional Rasch Measurement Analysis and Diagnostics
Version: 0.9.0
Authors@R: person("Josh", "McGrane", role = c("aut", "cre"),
    email = "drjoshmcgrane@gmail.com")
Description: Pairwise conditional maximum likelihood estimation of dichotomous
    and polytomous Rasch models (partial credit and rating scale) after
    Andrich and Luo (2003) and Zwinderman (1995), with standard errors from
    a Godambe sandwich estimator. Person measures are
    Warm's (1989) weighted likelihood estimates, computed per missing-data
    pattern. The diagnostic suite covers item and person fit residuals,
    infit and outfit, the item-trait interaction chi-square over class
    intervals, the person separation index with and
    without extremes, Cronbach's alpha, targeting, the score-to-measure
    table, test information, threshold and category diagnostics, residual
    principal-components dimensionality testing, local dependence by
    residual correlation, and differential item functioning by two-way
    residual analysis of variance over any number of person factors,
    factor-at-a-time or as a full factorial with Tukey HSD comparisons and
    false-discovery-rate adjustment. Also
    included: anchored estimation for test equating (individual threshold
    and average item-location anchors), common-item equating tests and
    plots, item splitting to resolve invariance violations, the many-facet
    Rasch model (Linacre 1989) for rated long-format data with facet
    severities, fit, and optional item-by-facet interactions, subtest
    formation for locally dependent items, multiple-choice scoring against a
    key with rest-measure distractor analysis and option curves, the Guttman
    scalogram with the coefficient of reproducibility, and the first software implementation of
    the extended frame of reference model (Humphry 2005; Humphry and Andrich
    2008), in which the unit of the latent scale differs across item-set by
    person-group frames: group units are estimated by person-free
    within-frame pairwise conditioning and set units by error-corrected
    person linking, all reported in a common arbitrary unit. A modern Shiny
    interface and a one-call exporter for every table and plot are included.
    Implemented from published measurement theory in base R, with no
    dependence on other estimation engines.
